ield"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">Politics</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">Trump Administration Tells Lawmakers China Trade Actions Are Needed; Robert Lighthizer cites U.S. intellectual property in testimony before skeptical Republicans</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>WASHINGTON—The Trump administration is looking at tariffs and investment restrictions as a way to pressure China to strengthen protection of American intellectual property, U.S. Trade Representative Robert Lighthizer told House lawmakers worried about a brewing trade war.</Para><Para>A White House spokesman said the president would take actions Thursday regarding "China's state-led, market-distorting efforts to force, pressure, and steal U.S. technologies and intellectual property."</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>The moves against China are necessary because the World Trade Organization "has proven to be wholly inadequate to deal with China's version of a state-dominated economy that rejects market principles," Mr. Lighthizer said in a formal statement at the House hearing.</Para><Para>Tariffs would be imposed unilaterally—without going to the WTO first, as is usually the case. However, a U.S trade official said the administration was also considering bringing a case at the World Trade Organization against China on practices that fall clearly under the jurisdiction of the Geneva-based trade body. That could be a way to try to recruit allies in a trade offensive against China.</Para><Para>The U.S. particularly objects to China requirements that many companies, including technology, autos and finance, do business in China through joint ventures. The U.S. contends that <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-to-ramp-up-trade-restraints-on-china-1521593091">Beijing pressures those companies to transfer advanced technology</ELink> to their Chinese partners.</Para><Para>Mr. Lighthizer said the administration had developed a computer algorithm to help the U.S. trade office decide which Chinese products to hit with tariffs. The goal is to pressure China to change practices, he said, while limiting harm to U.S. consumers and companies.</Para><Para>He said the U.S. trade office had spent "tens of thousands of hours" reading Chinese documents to better understand Chinese practices.</Para><Para>"Our view is we have a very serious problem losing our intellectual property, which is the single biggest advantage of the U.S. economy," Mr. Lighthizer said. "We are losing that to China in ways that aren't reflective of the underlying economics."</Para><Para>Chinese officials complain that the U.S. hasn't been specific about what steps they need to take to forestall U.S. tariffs. But the U.S. trade official, speaking after Mr. Lighthizer's House appearance, said the Trump administration had spent a good part of its first year in office talking with Chinese negotiators.</Para><Para>"As of today, the administration hasn't been satisfied with the types of responses we're getting from China," the official said.</Para><Para>The effort against China stems from <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-formally-begins-probe-of-china-technology-transfer-1503091630">a monthslong investigation</ELink> by the administration into Chinese intellectual-property practices that found the damage to U.S. companies from forced technology transfer is $30 billion annually. The proposed punitive measures that the administration is expected to announce on Thursday include tariffs on imports worth at least that amount, $30 billion.</Para><Para>The tariffs wouldn't be imposed immediately. Rather, U.S. industry would be given an opportunity to comment on which products should be subject to the duties. As part of the package, the White House will announce possible investment restrictions by Chinese firms in the U.S. and will direct the Treasury Department to outline rules governing investment from China.</Para><Para>Mr. Lighthizer was called before House lawmakers Wednesday and will face senators on Thursday to discuss the Trump administration's trade plans. Lawmakers have also summoned Commerce Secretary Wilbur Ross for testimony on Thursday.</Para><Para>Several Republican lawmakers have cautioned Mr. Trump in recent days that broad trade barriers risk hurting the economy and that Congress could take steps to rein in his trade authority.</Para><Para>"The challenge for any president in tariffs is to ensure that ultimately, you don't punish Americans for China's misbehavior," said Rep. Kevin Brady (R., Texas), chairman of the House Ways and Means Committee, on Monday. Mr. Brady said he is pushing for tariff exceptions for existing contracts, exclusions for products largely made abroad and exemptions for allies.</Para><Para><ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-names-key-partners-that-may-avoid-metals-tariffs-for-now-1521647613?tesla=y">Mr. Lighthizer also addressed</ELink> planned <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-to-meet-metal-workers-as-aides-ready-tariff-rollout-1520517821">steel and aluminum tariffs</ELink> imposed by the administration, telling lawmakers that several key U.S. allies and trading partners wouldn't face the levies until negotiations on possible tariff exemptions wrap up next month.</Para><Para>William Mauldin contributed to this article.</Para><Para>Write to Bob Davis at <ELink type="webpage" ref="mailto:bob.davis@wsj.com">bob.davis@wsj.com</ELink></Para><Para>More</Para><Para>* <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-names-key-partners-that-may-avoid-metals-tariffs-for-now-1521647613?tesla=y">EU, Australia, Argentina May Avoid Tariffs for Now</ELink></Para><Para>* <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/facing-u-s-tariffs-china-plans-countermeasures-1521632332">China to Target Trump's Base in Tariff Response</ELink></Para><Para>* <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-to-ramp-up-trade-restraints-on-china-1521593091?tesla=y">Trump to Ramp Up Trade Restraints on China</ELink></Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">By Bob Davis </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field"></Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">Copyright 2018 Dow Jones &amp; Company, Inc. All Rights Reserved. </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item><Item subtype="primary" size="0" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-trade-representative-says-wto-wholly-inadequate-to-deal-with-china-1521643030" type="webpage"></Item></AdocTOC></DistDoc>

